metadata.name: Circus of Life #146
metadata.description:
Circus of Life is a playful take on my Clusters Algorithm, the basis for a 3D VR app developed in concert with the brilliant minds at Leap Motion. Clusters is like John Conway's "Game of Life", where just a few elegant rules in a toy universe generate endless complexity. 

Here, we spawn twelve "species" of particles. Each species is variously attracted to or repulsed by the other species, giving rise to wandering colonies, invasive blobs, and oscillating particle storms. 

For this new work, I collaborated with fellow algorithmic artist Canton Becker who sweated over the colors and genomes to expand its universe. Coded in just 46KB of vanilla javascript, each animation is minted with its own color palette, behavior, and mutations. Some special rarities have been seeded as well. Watch as microbial dramas play out and galaxies spawn. Will your circus be obscene or sublime?

metadata.name: fx(word) #33
metadata.description:
"Word" is a single unit of language that has meaning and can be spoken or written.
You can make your favorite word or brief sentence into a work using no more than 10 characters of fx(params).
No matter what language you use or what it means, it's going to turn into a work of art.

--

To highlight the rarity of the params value you set, i have set only text to appear in the feature list.

--

This project is made in 100% pure code with p5js
By Thion, April 2023

metadata.name: MazeMerize #30
metadata.description:
A mesmerizing maze to watch as it unfolds, getting more dense at every step. This piece uses a technique called function collapse which is a way of selecting the next piece based on entropy... It doesn't really matter how this works but it does. 

You can interact with the piece with your keyboard: 

"Arrow UP" -> speed up the animation 
"Arrow DOWN" -> slow down the animation 
"P" -> pause/resume the animation

metadata.name: (fx)moji #124
metadata.description:
Emoji is the word for visual language, a way to express emotion without words.

From its humble origins as a Japanese emoticon in the mid-1990s, they exploded in popularity when appeared as a critical part of Apple's iPhone launch in 2007. The internationalization of emoji is an inexorable force, and today it is almost impossible to send a message without using one.

Emojis evolved as a way to communicate quickly and easily, and now they will evolve one more time and become an NFT generative art reborn as (fx)moji where basic geometric forms create a new full set of emojis expressions.

32 emojis,
7 Animations,

metadata.description:

The goal of this design is to display angular ideas placed on natural elements like the moon and sea in the simplest way possible.

metadata.name: ZOOM (4hwf) #81
metadata.description:
"Das System l√§sst keine √úberraschung zu. √úberraschung ist Ausdruck partieller Unkenntnis. √úberraschung weist auf Mangel von Wissen hin, deutet Leerstellen an. Bisher hatten sie keine Leerstellen festgestellt." ‚Äî Herbert W. Franke

ZOOM explores linear scaling of pixels by zooming into a noisy framebuffer. Various zoom levels are composed one below the other, becoming a cinematic animation through iteration of the hue values of the pixels in the framebuffer.

In Gedenken an Herbert W. Franke
Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: Dynamic generations #29
metadata.description:
A classic cellular automata updates its state with a static rule based on the state of its neighbor.

This collection was created with cellular automata with an extension of that idea. Here the state and the rule are updated based on the state of its neighbor, here the rule changes in every iteration, here the rule is dynamic.

That change moves cellular automata to another level of complexity.
